Note:
C# Parser Test Suite

Tests: 10 test files covering all major C# language features
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/csharp/csharp_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/csharp/csharp_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/io/file_io.runa" as File

@Reasoning:
Parses a C# source string into an AST through the real lexer -> parser
chain (create_csharp_lexer + create_csharp_parser + parse_program), the
same chain csharp_to_hir_from_source drives internally. Returns the AST
handle, or 0 on any failure, after tearing down the lexer and parser.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_csharp" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    Let lexer be proc create_csharp_lexer from Lexer with source, source_length
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let parser be proc create_csharp_parser from Parser with lexer
    If parser is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_csharp_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        Return 0
    End If
    Let ast be proc parse_program from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_csharp_parser from Parser with parser
    proc destroy_csharp_lexer from Lexer with lexer
    Return ast
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lightweight accumulator passed by reference to every test helper so the suite
can tally totals without relying on global state. Three Integer counters keep
the struct flat-loadable from memory_get_int64 at offsets 0/8/16.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Plain POD: total at offset 0, passed at offset 8, failed at offset 16.
Initialized to zero by main and mutated via memory_set_int64 inside
test_parse_file because results is passed as an Integer handle.
@End Implementation

Type called "TestResults":
    total as Integer
    passed as Integer
    failed as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the C# parser corpus. Exercises ten representative
.cs programs covering language surface most likely to regress (classes,
properties, lambdas, generics, async, events, control flow, operators,
nullable types, namespaces). Exit code maps to results.failed so CI
fails on any regression.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a TestResults on stack, calls test_parse_file once per program,
then prints aggregate counts. Returns 1 when any test failed, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 10 .cs programs parse to non-null AST with root node type 3000 -> exit 0
- Any single program failing to parse -> exit 1
- Empty corpus path -> read_file returns 0 -> failure counted, exit 1
@End TestCases

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be a value of type TestResults with total as 0, passed as 0, failed as 0

    proc print_header

    proc test_parse_file with "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/tests/csharp/programs/basic_class.cs", "Basic class", results
    proc test_parse_file with "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/tests/csharp/programs/properties.cs", "Properties", results
    proc test_parse_file with "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/tests/csharp/programs/lambda_expressions.cs", "Lambda expressions", results
    proc test_parse_file with "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/tests/csharp/programs/generics.cs", "Generics", results
    proc test_parse_file with "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/tests/csharp/programs/async_await.cs", "Async/await", results
    proc test_parse_file with "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/tests/csharp/programs/events_delegates.cs", "Events and delegates", results
    proc test_parse_file with "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/tests/csharp/programs/control_flow.cs", "Control flow", results
    proc test_parse_file with "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/tests/csharp/programs/operators.cs", "Operators", results
    proc test_parse_file with "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/tests/csharp/programs/nullable_types.cs", "Nullable types", results
    proc test_parse_file with "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/tests/csharp/programs/namespaces_using.cs", "Namespaces and using", results

    proc print_results with results

    If results.failed is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-program parse check used by main as the per-corpus probe. Pulled
out so each program path is one call site and so the results counter
mutation logic lives in exactly one place.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Increment results.total.
2. read_file(content); null -> record failure ("Failed to read file").
3. parse_csharp(content); null AST -> record failure.
4. memory_get_int64(ast, 0) must equal 3000 (CSHARP_PROGRAM) -> otherwise
   "Invalid root node type" failure.
5. On success, increment results.passed and print [PASS].
6. Always deallocate(content) before returning on the success path; the
   failure paths that already deallocated must not double-free.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- programs/basic_class.cs -> AST root 3000, results.passed += 1
- Non-existent path -> read_file == 0 -> failure with "Failed to read file"
- Malformed .cs -> parse_csharp returns 0 -> failure with "Parser returned null AST"
- Valid lex but wrong root tag (synthetic) -> failure with "Invalid root node type"
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parse_file" takes file_path as Integer, test_name as Integer, results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let _rtot1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 0, _rtot1 plus 1

    Let content be proc read_entire_file from File with file_path

    If content is equal to 0:
        proc print_test_failure with test_name, "Failed to read file"
        Let _rfal1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal1 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse_csharp with content

    If ast is equal to 0:
        proc print_test_failure with test_name, "Parser returned null AST"
        proc deallocate from Layout with content
        Let _rfal2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal2 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Verify AST root node type (CSHARP_PROGRAM = 3000)
    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 0

    If node_type is not equal to 3000:
        proc print_test_failure with test_name, "Invalid root node type"
        proc deallocate from Layout with content
        Let _rfal3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal3 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    proc print_test_success with test_name
    proc deallocate from Layout with content
    Let _rpas1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 8, _rpas1 plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Suite banner emitted once at startup. Separator width matches the title
so visual scanning of CI logs lines up.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate the title and a 22-character "=" rule via StringCore, print
each via the runtime print primitive, then deallocate. Always returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_header" returns Integer:
    proc print with "C# Parser Test Suite"
    proc print with "======================"
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits a "[PASS] <test_name>" line. Kept separate from print_test_failure
so grep "[FAIL]" on CI output cleanly isolates regressions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[PASS] " prefix string, print it, then print the caller-owned
test_name pointer. Caller retains ownership of test_name; only the
prefix string is freed here.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_test_success" takes test_name as Integer returns Integer:
    proc print with "[PASS] "
    proc print with test_name
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits "[FAIL] <test_name>: <reason>" — both name and reason are caller
owned. Required so a CI failure shows which program failed AND why
(missing file vs. parser-null vs. wrong root tag) without grepping
upstream context.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[FAIL] " prefix, print prefix, print test_name, print ": ",
print reason, deallocate prefix. test_name and reason are not freed.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_test_failure" takes test_name as Integer, reason as Integer returns Integer:
    proc print with "[FAIL] "
    proc print with test_name
    proc print with ": "
    proc print with reason
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Final summary footer with total/passed/failed counts. Reads counters
directly via struct field access (results.total, etc.) rather than
memory_get_int64 because the type-checked path is preferred at the
report site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print "======================" rule, "Test Results:" heading, then
three "Total: N", "Passed: N", "Failed: N" lines. Each label string
is allocated, printed, and deallocated; numeric values use print_int.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_results" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    proc print with "======================"
    proc print with "Test Results:"

    proc print with "Total: "
    proc print_int with results.total

    proc print with "Passed: "
    proc print_int with results.passed

    proc print with "Failed: "
    proc print_int with results.failed

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Self-contained integer printer so the test harness has no dependency on
stdlib formatting (those modules pull in heavyweight allocators not yet
wired in this layer). Handles zero and negative values explicitly so
single-digit edge cases don't fall through the divmod loop.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. If value == 0, print "0" and return early.
2. Allocate a 32-byte buffer, walk position from 31 downward, writing
   ASCII digits (48 + value % 10) right-to-left.
3. For negative values, work on -temp during the loop and prepend '-'
   (45) at the final position.
4. Advance position by 1 to skip past the last decrement, then print
   buffer + position as a zero-terminated C string.
5. Deallocate the 32-byte buffer.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_int" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        proc print with "0"
        Return 1
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    Note: Reserve the final byte as the NUL terminator so print reads a
    Note: bounded C string; digits are written from index 30 downward.
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, 31, 0
    Let position be 30
    Let temp be value

    If temp is less than 0:
        Set temp to -temp
    End If

    While temp is greater than 0:
        Let digit be temp modulo by 10
        Let char be 48 plus digit
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, char
        Set position to position minus 1
        Set temp to temp divided by 10
    End While

    If value is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, 45
        Set position to position minus 1
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1
    Let str_ptr be buffer plus position
    proc print with str_ptr

    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: End of C# Parser Test Suite
